data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Yuanhe, he was a Wei General who originally worked for Henei emperor Wang Kuang. He became famous for rejecting Dong Zhuo's recruitment efforts and later became the subordinate of Xiahou Dun. When Xiahou Dun was abducted, it was because of Han Hao's decisive actions that he survived. In the first year of the Jian'an era (196 AD), he suggested the harvesting plan to Cao Cao and as such was honored as a military officer. After working as a mid-level military officer, he managed the imperial guards together with Shi Huan, blocking feudal lords.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Cao Wei General. In the second year of the Taihe era (228 AD), Shu Han emperor Zhuge Liang surrounded Chencang, and Wei senior general Cao Zhen's army resisted until the Shu ran out of rations and retreated. Wang Shuang was ordered to pursue the Shu army, but was defeated by Zhuge Liang.

data.Strength: Commanding general, good at leading close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Cao Wei General. In his early years he was once under Cao Ren. In the third year of the Qinglong era (235 AD), Shu General Ma Dai invaded. The army, led by Niu Jin, achieved complete victory. In the second year of the Jingchu era (238 AD), allies such as Hu Zun followed Si Mayi in the rebellion against Gong Sunyuan and pacified Liaodong. In the end, he was made a general.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Zihe, he was the younger brother of Cao Ren, Wei's Great Minister of War, and commander of the Tiger Warriors. In the tenth year of the Jian'an era (205 AD), he attacked Nanpi under military staff officer Sikong's identity. The frustrated Cao Cao faced difficulties and led his elite cavalry to behead Yuan Tan. In the 12th year of the Jian’an Era (207 AD), following the northern conquest of Wuwan, the commander of the Tiger Warriors captured the leader Ta Dun. Due to his past achievements, he was named Gaolinghou.

data.Strength: Balanced leader, can lead close combat infantry and close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Zixiao, he was the younger brother of Cao Cao and a famous Wei general. He earned respect through Cao Cao's conquest in the North. After the Battle of the Red Cliffs, he was entrusted with the task of guarding Jiangling and resisting tens of thousands of Zhou Yu's men. Because he led only around ten cavalry from the lineup to save Niu Jin, Chen Jiao became known as the "Outstanding Man". During the Battle of Xiangfan, they almost ran out of ammunition and food supplies, leading to the retreat of Guan Yu's army. Due to their victories, he became known as a senior general, the Great Minister of War, and earned the noble title of Chen Hou.

data.Strength: Commanding general, good at leading ranged infantry and close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Degui, he was born of Xiangyang nobility and had a good relationship with Cao Cao. His sister was the second wife of general Liu Biao, who he helped in stabilizing Jingzhou. He was soon appointed as the general military advisor of Zhennan. When Liu Bei was in Jingzhou, Cai Mao, Kuai Yue, and others tried to harm him, but did not succeed. After the death of Liu Biao, Cai Mao and Zhang Yun wanted the young generation to take over and supported the second son of Liu Biao, Liu Cong, in taking over the position. After Cao Cao, Cai Mao became the Changshui field officer and became known as Hanyang Tinghou.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Xiahou Yuan, also known as Miaocai, was a famous general at the end of the Eastern Han from Qiao of Pei. This general conquered the west and was known as Chang Tinghou. He started military endeavors with Cao Cao, transporting rations during the Battle of Guandu. From the sixth to the sixteenth year of the Jian'an era, he commanded the stabilization of Runan, Jinan, and Le'an, and the Qian River rebellions. In the seventeenth year of the Jian'an era, he took the position of a mid-ranking general and began the Battle of the Outer Pass against Ma Chao and Han Sui. Xiahou Yuan was strong and good at long-range raids. He Became known as the Western General after annihilating the Qiang Hu forces, Xiliang's elite traitors. He died during the twenty fourth year of the Jian'an era, in a battle on Mount Dingjun.

data.Strength: Intelligent leader, can lead close combat infantry and close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Ma Su, also known as Youchang, was a Shu Han official and general from Yicheng, Xiangyang, and the brother of Ma Liang. Ma Su was talented even when he was young, and was called one of "The Five Mas" along with his brothers. After serving in Jingzhou, he went with Liu Bei into Shu. Zhuge Liang saw his talent and thought highly of him. Near his end, Liu Bei once warned Zhuge Liang to be wary of Ma Su, but Zhuge Liang trusted him and discussed military affairs with him. In the sixth year of Jianxing, Ma Su was the pioneer of Zhuge Liang's northern expedition. Ma Su didn't listen to Wang Ping's persuasions and his team was assigned to Nanshan. In the end, defeat occurred when Zhang He cut off their water supply. Ma Su was later killed by Zhuge Liang and died a tearful death.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Chen Dao, also known as Shuzhi, was a Shu Han General and governor of Yong'an from Runan, Yuzhou. Known to be loyal and brave, Chen Dao went to Liu Bei when serving as the highest ranking official of Yuzhou. This started a long battle with Liu Bei, with him leading the elite Shu Han forces, the Baier soldiers. During the Jianxing era, he became the "General Who Subdues the West". In the fourth year of the Jianxing era, he was stationed in Badong as Yongan governor, and died at his post.

data.Strength: Balanced leader, can lead close combat infantry and ranged cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Hansheng, Huang Zhong was a famous general of the Eastern Han from Nanyang. He was originally one of Liu Biao's royal security members, stationed in Changsha. In the thirteenth year of Jian'an, following the fall of the Jingzhou army to Cao Cao, he surrendered once again to Liu Bei. From the eighteenth to the nineteenth year of the Jian'an era, Huang Zhong performed outstandingly during Liu Bei's attack on Yizhou's Liu Zhang and was appointed as the general of enemy invasions. In the twenty-fourth year of the Jian'an era, Huang Zhong led his troops to attack Cao Cao's subordinate, the famous general Xiahou Yuan, during the battle of Mount Dingjun, killing him in the process. After Liu Bei became the emperor of Hanzhong, his title was changed to the later general, a high ranking position. The following year, Huang Zhong died of illness and was known as Ganghou.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Gongmiao, this Wu general was famous for his luxurious armory and for being a defender of honor. When submitting to the authority of the Sun, he helped Sun Ce stabilize the rebellions and set up Jian'an, Hanxing, and Nanping in Minyue. After Sun Quan came to the throne, He Qi, based on his victory against the Shanyue and pacification of many places, was honored as a Pingdong field officer, assistant general, and fenwu general. In the twelfth year of Jian'an, (215 AD), Sun Quan was defeated by Wei General Zhang Liao, after a collision with He Qi's army, but he was able to get away. He became a general in the end and was honored as Shanyinhou.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Famous general of the Eastern Wu, known as one of the "Jiang Biao Brave Ministers" with Cheng Pu, Huang Gai, and others. Because of his strength from a young age and capability in riding and shooting, his potential was recognized by Sun Jian. He served through the three generations of Sun Jian, Sun Ce, and Sun Quan, and was involved in the Battle of the Red Cliffs, the Yiling War, and had many notable exploits. In the second year of the Huangwu era (223 AD), he was honored as Zhaowu General, Shichenghou, and military governor. In the sixth year of the Huangwu era (227 AD) he led the Solution Soldiers in a crusade against Danyang and won.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Gongfu, this famous general of the Eastern Wu was known as one of the "Jiang Biao Brave Ministers" along with Cheng Pu, Han Dang, and others. He experienced the three generations of Sun Jian, Sun Ce, and Sun Quan and was a subject who selected officials, and served as a county official, and after Sun Jian fought the north and south, he was worshiped as the other Sima. After Sun Quan took the throne, he took orders to pacify all parts of Shanyue. During the Battle of the Red Cliffs, he suggested a plan for a fire attack, helped Zhou Yu defeat Cao Cao's invading army, and became known as the Wufeng royal security general. Due to his efforts in the crusades against the Shanyue in Yiyang county, he was honored as assistant general.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry and ranged infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Gan Ning, also known as Xingba, was from Linjiang, and was officer to the Xiling Prefecture and a noble general. Known as a raider in his youth, he gathered with others to loot ships and was known as the "Brocade Sail Thief". He later quit to learn from philosophers and decided not to join Huang Zu's army, allying with Sun Quan. He performed well in the attack against Huang Zu's army and attacked Cao's army in Wulun during the Battle of the Red Cliffs. Later, in the battle against the south, Gan Ning led 100 people to capture Yiling. He pushed back Guan Yu's army in Yiyang and in the eighteenth year of the Jian'an era, made triumphant gains while leading 100 cavalrymen to attack the Cao camp at night. He achieved repeated military exploits later on, during the Battle of Hefei in Wancheng, but died of illness in the twenty fifth year of the Jian'an era.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Also known as Wenxiang, this famous general of the Eastern Wu was known as one of the "Jiang Biao Brave Ministers" along with Cheng Pu, and others. In the twenty-second year of the Jian'an era (217 AD) Cao Cao sent troops to Ruxukou where the Wu army encountered strong winds. The ancient ships were blown towards the enemy, igniting their fear. Only Xu Sheng was able to break through the gale and saw success. In the fifth year of the Huangchu era, (222 AD), he confronted Wei general Cao Xiu with a small amount of soldiers from across the river. As a result of his success, he became known as the Andong general, a noble of Wuhu. In the fifth year of the Huangchu era (224 AD), Cao led troops to the east, so Xu Sheng used diversionary troops to make the enemy retreat, a tactic admired by all.

data.Strength: Commanding general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Sun Shi (also known as Sun Shangxiang) was from Fuchun, Wu, and was known as "Sister of a General Who Attacks Barbarians of the Eastern Han, Sun Quan". She became Liu Bei's wife and was clever with a strong character. She often led around 100 female servants carrying knives. Even Liu Bei was worried about starting trouble with her. In the seventeenth year of Jian'an, Liu Bei occupied Shu and the relations of the Sun and Liu families worsened. Sun Quan sent soldiers to take back Madame Sun. Sun originally wanted to take Liu Chan away, but she was recaptured by Zhao Yun's army. Sun did not show up on any records after that.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat infantry
data.SoldierDescription: Hu Che'er, Xiliang army officer at the end of the Eastern Han, was a confidant of Zhang Xiu and personal friend of Jia Xu. After the Battle of Wancheng, he surrendered to Cao Cao with Zhang Xiu and received great rewards. Because Zhang Xiu was afraid Cao Cao would bribe Hu Che'er, he worked hard to launch a rebellion. Later, Hu Che'er and Zhang Xiu again surrendered to Cao Cao.

data.SoldierDescription: Macrinus (*Full Name: Marcus Nonius Macrinus),Marcus Nonius Macrinus was a famous general and politician during the Roman Empire. He was from Brescia, Northern Italy and helped the Roman Empire achieve numerous military achievements. This led him to serve as a province governor and to become one of Marcus Aurelius' trusted advisers. He was also one of the main figures that Maximus, from the movie "Gladiator", was based on.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Hua Xiong (also known as Ye Xiong) was under Dong Zhuo's command at the end of the Eastern Han as a military account governor. In the second year of the Chuping era, the northeastern warlords united against Dong Zhuo. Lu Bu, Hu Zhen, and Hua Xiong occupied and seized Yangrencheng, but Hu Zhen and Lu Bu didn't work well together, which caused difficulty during the siege. In addition, Lu Bu spread rumors that the enemy had attacked, allowing Sun Jian to seize the opportunity to win back the town. In the confusion, Hua Xiong was killed by Sun Jian's tracking army.

data.Strength: Military general, good at leading close combat cavalry
data.SoldierDescription: Gongsun Zan, also known as Bogui, was a warlord near the end of the Eastern Han from Lingzhi, Liaoxi, and was Zhangshi in the early years of Youzhou. He often fought fierce battles with the northern Hu people. In the second year of the Chuping era, Gongsun Zan's 20,000 troops annihilated over 10,000 Qingzhou Yellow Scarves in Dongguang. In the second year of the Chuping era, he began to fight with Yuan Shao for control over Jizhou. The following year, he attacked and killed Liu Yu, was promoted to general, and controlled all of Youzhou. In Yuyang, in the second year of Xingping, Bao Qiu was defeated by Liu Yu's remaining troops and retreated to the capital. Later, he had a confrontation with Yuan Shao and Liu He's troops, and in the fourth year of Jian'an, Gongsun Zan was lured out and defeated by Yuan Shao. He ultimately ended his life through self-immolation.

data.Strength: Balanced leader, can lead all sorts of troops
data.SoldierDescription: Rebel leader of the Yellow Scarves. In the first year of the Zhongping era (184 AD), he led the uprising in Yingchuan, defeating the Han right royal security general Zhu Jun. He took this opportunity to besiege Huangfu Song in Changshe, alarming officials across the land. However, Bo Cai set up camp in the adjacent grasslands, and when huge winds descended on him, he found himself trapped in Huang Pusong's ring of fire, forcing him to retreat to Yangdi.
